But there can be no manner of doubt about the origin of the same or a similar saying in Webster‚ who, like Montaigne, uses it in relation to the question of self- slaughter. Montaigne notes instances of men who have attempted, but failed, to kill themselves outright, courage having deserted them in their extremity. The smarting wounds they inflicted upon themselves served but to intensify the anguish of mind they already suffered, thus adding to their torments.
